BACKGROUND: This study evaluated the cost-effectiveness of replacing standard 
intravenous therapy (taxane) with oral S-1 therapy for first-line metastatic 
breast cancer treatment.
METHODS: This cost-effectiveness analysis was based on data from a randomized 
phase III trial (SELECT BC). As cost-effectiveness was a secondary endpoint of 
the SELECT BC trial, some of the randomized patients participated in an EQ-5D 
survey (N = 391) and health economic survey (N = 146). The EQ-5D responses, 
claims, and prescription data were collected for as long as possible until 
death. The expected quality-adjusted life years (QALY) obtained from each 
treatment were calculated using patient-level EQ-5D data, and the expected cost 
was calculated using patient-level claim data. The analysis was performed from 
the perspective of public healthcare payers.
RESULTS: The estimated EQ-5D least-square means and 95% CI up to 48 months were 
0.764 (95% CI, 0.741-0.782) and 0.742 (95% CI, 0.720-0.764) in the S-1 and 
taxane arms, respectively. The expected QALY was 2.11 for the S-1 arm and 2.04 
for the taxane arm, with expected costs of JPY 5.13 million (USD 46,600) and JPY 
5.56 million (USD 50,500), respectively. These results show that S-1 is 
cost-saving. According to probabilistic sensitivity analysis, S-1 was dominant 
with a probability of 63%. When the willingness to pay (WTP) value was JPY 5 
million (USD 45,500) per QALY, the probability of being cost-effective was 92%.
CONCLUSIONS: Our results show that the introduction of oral S-1 therapy for 
metastatic breast cancer is highly likely to be cost-effective.
